  "prompt": "How difficult is it to get accepted to a master's program in civil engineering?",
  "response": "The difficulty of getting accepted to a master's program in civil engineering varies depending on several factors:\n\n1. Academic requirements:\n- Typically require a bachelor's degree in civil engineering or a related field\n- Minimum GPA often around 3.0-3.5\n- Strong undergraduate academic performance\n- Competitive GRE scores\n\n2. School selectivity:\n- Top-tier universities have more competitive admissions\n- Less selective schools may have easier acceptance rates\n- Public vs. private schools can differ in requirements\n\n3. Application components:\n- Undergraduate transcripts\n- Letters of recommendation\n- Personal statement/statement of purpose\n- Research experience or internships\n- Professional work experience\n- Research alignment with faculty interests\n\n4. Additional factors:\n- International students may need TOEFL/IELTS scores\n- Some programs require specific prerequisite courses\n- Some schools have limited cohort sizes\n\n5. Competitive areas:\n- Highly ranked programs are more challenging to enter\n- Programs with strong research funding\n- Schools in major metropolitan areas\n\nOverall difficulty ranges from moderately challenging to very competitive, depending on the specific program and individual qualifications. Strong academic credentials and relevant experience improve acceptance chances.",
